It's old, but it's beautiful.

228
00:17:34,253 --> 00:17:38,019
From above the corpse of a woman
who'd just leapt to her death.

229
00:17:38,290 --> 00:17:42,283
There's blood around her head,
like a halo...

230
00:17:42,494 --> 00:17:45,622
...and her leg's buckled underneath,
her arm's snapped like a twig...

231
00:17:47,032 --> 00:17:49,523
...but her face is so serene...

232
00:17:50,069 --> 00:17:52,128
...so at peace.

233
00:17:52,638 --> 00:17:54,538
And I think it's because
when she died...

234
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:58,141
...she could feel the wind
against her face.

235
00:18:03,482 --> 00:18:07,714
I don't know how to kill Harold Crick.
That's why they sent you.

236
00:18:08,287 --> 00:18:10,255
Yes, to help you.

237
00:18:11,490 --> 00:18:12,957
How are you gonna help me?

238
00:18:13,158 --> 00:18:15,285
You, who never thinks
of leaping off buildings?

239
00:18:15,494 --> 00:18:18,088
What great inspiration
will you bestow on me?

240
00:18:18,297 --> 00:18:20,595
I'll tell you, the quaint ideas
you've gathered...

241
00:18:20,799 --> 00:18:22,824
...in your adorable career
as an "assistant"...

242
00:18:23,035 --> 00:18:25,868
...are to no avail
when faced with killing a man.

243
00:18:26,572 --> 00:18:28,335
I understand.

244
00:18:28,674 --> 00:18:31,370
Do you? I can't just...

245
00:18:38,283 --> 00:18:39,580
As much as I would like to...

246
00:18:39,785 --> 00:18:43,516
...I cannot simply throw
Harold Crick off a building.

247
00:18:50,195 --> 00:18:55,428
Miss Eiffel. Kay. I've been
an author's assistant for 11 years.

248
00:18:55,634 --> 00:18:58,398
I've helped more than 20 authors
complete more than 35 books...

249
00:18:58,604 --> 00:19:00,663
...and I've never missed the deadline.

250
00:19:00,873 --> 00:19:03,865
And I have never gone back to the
publisher to ask for more time.

251
00:19:04,076 --> 00:19:07,512
Now, I will be available to you
every minute of every day...

252
00:19:07,713 --> 00:19:11,342
...until the final punctuation
is embedded on the very last page.

253
00:19:11,550 --> 00:19:15,919
I do not like loud music.
I do not abide narcotics.

254
00:19:16,221 --> 00:19:21,420
And I will gladly and quietly
help you kill Harold Crick.

255
00:19:30,335 --> 00:19:34,704
I had a very interesting little convo
with someone in your section.

256
00:19:34,907 --> 00:19:36,101
Yeah?

257
00:19:37,476 --> 00:19:40,240
They said you were feeling
a little wibbly-wobbly.

258
00:19:43,382 --> 00:19:45,441
Catch a little cubicle fever?

259
00:19:45,984 --> 00:19:47,952
Oh, I don't know. I think I'm okay.

260
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:53,920
Harold, a tree doesn't think
it's a tree...

261
00:19:54,259 --> 00:19:56,318
...it is a tree.

262
00:19:56,828 --> 00:19:59,626
<i>Why was Harold talking to this man?</i>

263
00:20:00,132 --> 00:20:02,600
<i>This man was an idiot.</i>

264
00:20:02,801 --> 00:20:08,296
<i>This man used words like</i>
<i>"wibbly-wobbly" and "convo."</i>

265
00:20:08,774 --> 00:20:11,902
<i>And explained that trees were trees.</i>

266
00:20:12,444 --> 00:20:14,173
O<i>f course trees were trees.</i>

267
00:20:14,379 --> 00:20:16,108
<i>Harold knew trees were trees.</i>

268
00:20:16,315 --> 00:20:17,942
I am going to believe you, Harold.

269
00:20:18,150 --> 00:20:20,584
<i>What Harold didn't know</i>
<i>was why he couldn't shake...</i>

270
00:20:20,786 --> 00:20:23,346
<i>... the smell of brownies</i>
<i>from his senses.</i>

271
00:20:23,555 --> 00:20:28,015
<i>Why Ms. Pascal had made</i>
<i>his fingertips quiver and lips go numb.</i>

272
00:20:29,528 --> 00:20:30,893
Harold?

273
00:20:33,298 --> 00:20:35,425
Yes? Sorry.

274
00:20:36,034 --> 00:20:38,195
What's going on, Harold?

275
00:20:39,705 --> 00:20:40,967
Well...

276
00:20:43,375 --> 00:20:46,503
Nothing. Everything's fine.

277
00:20:48,780 --> 00:20:51,749
Listen, according to your records...

278
00:20:51,950 --> 00:20:56,614
...you haven't taken vacation
in a few years now.

279
00:20:56,822 --> 00:20:59,950
Let's say you take a little break.

280
00:21:00,559 --> 00:21:02,925
Use some of that vaca time.

281
00:21:04,563 --> 00:21:07,896
Yeah. I'll think about it.

282
00:21:12,237 --> 00:21:13,602
Harold.

283
00:21:15,540 --> 00:21:20,341
I'm not really supposed to do this,
but...

284
00:21:39,631 --> 00:21:42,156
<i>Harold assumed his watch</i>
<i>was simply on the fritz...</i>

285
00:21:42,367 --> 00:21:46,167
<i>... and never even considered that it</i>
<i>might be trying to tell him something.</i>

286
00:21:49,107 --> 00:21:52,167
<i>In fact, Harold had never once</i>
<i>paid attention to his watch...</i>

287
00:21:52,377 --> 00:21:54,242
<i>... other than to find out the time.</i>

288
00:21:54,446 --> 00:21:58,712
<i>And, honestly,</i>
<i>it drove his watch crazy.</i>

289
00:21:59,117 --> 00:22:01,517
<i>And so, on this particular</i>
<i>Wednesday evening...</i>

290
00:22:01,720 --> 00:22:05,087
<i>... as Harold waited for the bus,</i>
<i>his watch suddenly...</i>

291
00:22:05,924 --> 00:22:07,789
<i>... stopped.</i>

292
00:22:09,528 --> 00:22:11,291
Sorry, does anyone have the time?

293
00:22:12,230 --> 00:22:15,461
- Yeah, I got 6:18.
- Thanks.

294
00:22:15,667 --> 00:22:21,765
<i>Thus Harold's watch thrust him</i>
<i>into the immitigable path of fate.</i>

295
00:22:21,973 --> 00:22:26,239
<i>Little did he know that this simple,</i>
<i>seemingly innocuous act...</i>

296
00:22:26,445 --> 00:22:29,243
<i>... would result in his imminent death.</i>

297
00:22:29,581 --> 00:22:31,708
What? What?

298
00:22:31,917 --> 00:22:33,908
Hey! Hello?

299
00:22:34,386 --> 00:22:35,785
What?

300
00:22:36,488 --> 00:22:37,750
Why?

301
00:22:38,490 --> 00:22:40,151
Why my death?

302
00:22:40,392 --> 00:22:41,791
Hello!

303
00:22:42,427 --> 00:22:44,486
Excuse me!

304
00:22:44,963 --> 00:22:46,658
When?

305
00:22:47,366 --> 00:22:49,357
How imminent?

306
00:22:50,302 --> 00:22:51,894
Okay, where are you?

307
00:22:59,277 --> 00:23:03,441
"Harold would brush his 32 teeth
72 times."

308
00:23:03,949 --> 00:23:07,510
Why won't you say anything?
I heard you.

309
00:23:08,153 --> 00:23:10,314
"That would result
in his imminent death."

310
00:23:10,956 --> 00:23:12,753
I heard you!

311
00:23:13,458 --> 00:23:15,085
Come on, you stupid voice.

312
00:23:15,293 --> 00:23:17,853
"Harold frantically grabbed his lamp.

313
00:23:18,830 --> 00:23:23,290
Harold, incensed, shook the hell
out of it for no apparent reason!

314
00:23:23,502 --> 00:23:27,165
And smashed it on the ground,
kicking it repeatedly!

315
00:23:28,907 --> 00:23:31,774
Harold took his Kleenex box,
threw it across the room...

316
00:23:31,977 --> 00:23:33,604
...then stormed the closet!"

317
00:23:36,314 --> 00:23:38,373
Come on. Say something.

318
00:23:40,585 --> 00:23:43,145
Something. Say something!

319
00:23:44,389 --> 00:23:46,380
Say something!

320
00:23:53,331 --> 00:23:56,164
"Harold, distraught..."

321
00:23:58,069 --> 00:23:59,559
God.

322
00:24:00,038 --> 00:24:02,131
"Harold, distraught..."

323
00:24:05,210 --> 00:24:06,734
"Harold..."

324
00:24:10,882 --> 00:24:15,114
<i>I'm afraid what you're describing</i>
<i>is schizophrenia.</i>

325
00:24:17,522 --> 00:24:22,824
No. No. It's not schizophrenia.
It's just a voice in my head.

326
00:24:23,028 --> 00:24:26,691
I mean, the voice isn't telling me
to do anything.

327
00:24:26,898 --> 00:24:29,389
It's telling me what I've already done.

328
00:24:29,768 --> 00:24:32,601
Accurately
and with a better vocabulary.

329
00:24:33,472 --> 00:24:36,407
Mr. Crick, you have a voice
speaking to you.

330
00:24:36,875 --> 00:24:40,003
No, not to me, about me.

331
00:24:40,479 --> 00:24:45,416
I'm somehow involved
in some sort of story.

332
00:24:45,817 --> 00:24:48,377
Like I'm a character in my own life.

333
00:24:48,920 --> 00:24:52,720
But the problem is
that the voice comes and goes.

334
00:24:53,024 --> 00:24:56,152
Like there are other parts of the story
not being told to me...

335
00:24:56,361 --> 00:24:59,922
...and I need to find out what those
other parts are before it's too late.

336
00:25:00,398 --> 00:25:03,128
Before the story concludes
with your death.

337
00:25:03,335 --> 00:25:04,700
Yes.

338
00:25:05,504 --> 00:25:07,972
Mr. Crick, I hate to sound
like a broken record...

339
00:25:08,173 --> 00:25:10,471
...but that's schizophrenia.

340
00:25:11,877 --> 00:25:16,507
You don't sound like a broken record,
but it's just not schizophrenia.

341
00:25:17,582 --> 00:25:20,415
What if what I said was true?

342
00:25:20,619 --> 00:25:25,886
Hypothetically speaking,
if I was part of a story, a narrative...

343
00:25:26,091 --> 00:25:29,959
...even if it was only in my mind...

344
00:25:30,295 --> 00:25:31,887
...what would you suggest that I do?

345
00:25:32,831 --> 00:25:35,925
I would suggest
you take prescribed medication.

346
00:25:37,269 --> 00:25:38,896
Other than that.

347
00:25:39,104 --> 00:25:41,004
I don't know.

348
00:25:41,640 --> 00:25:45,701
I suppose I would send you to see
someone who knows about literature.

349
00:25:48,013 --> 00:25:49,207
Okay.

350
00:25:50,115 --> 00:25:53,175
Yeah. That's a good idea.

351
00:25:53,885 --> 00:25:55,614
Thank you.

352
00:25:56,254 --> 00:25:58,848
So you're the gentleman
who called me about the narrator.

353
00:25:59,057 --> 00:26:01,719
- Yes.
- This narrator says you're gonna die.

354
00:26:01,927 --> 00:26:03,053
Yes.

355
00:26:03,261 --> 00:26:06,719
- How long has it given you to live?
- I don't know.

356
00:26:06,998 --> 00:26:10,263
Dramatic irony.
It'll fuck you every time.

357
00:26:11,269 --> 00:26:13,260
- So you crazy or what?
- Well...

358
00:26:13,471 --> 00:26:15,496
Are you allowed to say that
to crazy people?

359
00:26:15,707 --> 00:26:17,834
- I don't know.
- Oh, well. How many stairs...

360
00:26:18,043 --> 00:26:20,341
...in the hallway out there?
- What?

361
00:26:20,545 --> 00:26:22,809
You were counting them
as we walked, weren't you?

362
00:26:23,014 --> 00:26:24,208
No.

363
00:26:24,416 --> 00:26:26,111
Of course.
What bank do you work at?

364
00:26:26,318 --> 00:26:28,479
No bank. IRS agent.

365
00:26:29,120 --> 00:26:30,212
- Married?
- No.

366
00:26:30,422 --> 00:26:31,446
Ever?

367
00:26:31,656 --> 00:26:34,591
Engaged to an auditor.
She left me for an actuary.

368
00:26:34,793 --> 00:26:38,559
- How heartbreaking. Live alone?
- Yes.

369
00:26:39,864 --> 00:26:43,163
- Any pets?
- No.

370
00:26:43,535 --> 00:26:47,403
- Friends?
- No. Well, Dave at work.

371
00:26:48,640 --> 00:26:51,803
I see. The narrator,
exactly what does he sound like?

372
00:26:52,010 --> 00:26:53,341
It's a woman.

373
00:26:54,579 --> 00:26:55,876
A woman.

374
00:26:56,081 --> 00:26:58,208
- Is it a familiar woman?
- No.

375
00:26:58,416 --> 00:27:00,111
Someone you know?

376
00:27:00,986 --> 00:27:02,180
No.

377
00:27:02,387 --> 00:27:05,015
Did you have enough time
to count the tiles in the bathroom?

378
00:27:05,590 --> 00:27:07,558
I wasn't counting the tiles.

379
00:27:08,994 --> 00:27:10,757
- Coffee?
- No, thank you.

380
00:27:10,962 --> 00:27:12,429
- Sure?
- Yes.

381
00:27:13,598 --> 00:27:16,066
So this woman, the voice,
told you you're gonna die?

382
00:27:16,267 --> 00:27:18,497
She didn't tell me.
She doesn't know I can hear her.

383
00:27:18,703 --> 00:27:20,500
- But she said it.
- Yes.

384
00:27:20,705 --> 00:27:21,933
And you believed her.

385
00:27:22,774 --> 00:27:24,571
She's been right
about a few other things.

386
00:27:24,776 --> 00:27:28,337
- Such as?
- How I felt about work.

387
00:27:28,546 --> 00:27:31,014
- You dislike your work?
- Yes.

388
00:27:32,617 --> 00:27:35,245
Well, not the most insightful voice
in the world, is it?

389
00:27:35,487 --> 00:27:37,751
First thing on a list
of what Americans hate: Work.

390
00:27:37,956 --> 00:27:40,618
Second, traffic. Third, missing socks.
See what I'm saying?

391
00:27:40,825 --> 00:27:41,792
Sort of.

392
00:27:41,993 --> 00:27:43,984
I told you you were gonna die,
you believe me?

393
00:27:44,195 --> 00:27:45,526
- No.
- Why?

394
00:27:45,730 --> 00:27:47,095
I don't know you.

395
00:27:47,298 --> 00:27:49,357
- But you don't know this narrator.
- Well...

396
00:27:50,635 --> 00:27:55,197
- Okay, Mr. Crick, I can't help you.
- Why?

397
00:27:55,407 --> 00:27:58,467
Well, I'm not an expert in crazy,
I'm an expert in literature theory.

398
00:27:58,677 --> 00:28:01,111
And I gotta tell you, thus far...

399
00:28:01,312 --> 00:28:04,213
...there doesn't seem to be a single
literary thing about you.

400
00:28:04,416 --> 00:28:07,715
I don't doubt you hear a voice,
but it couldn't possibly be a narrator...

401
00:28:07,919 --> 00:28:10,945
...because, frankly, there doesn't seem
to be much to narrate.

402
00:28:11,156 --> 00:28:13,590
Beside that, this semester
I'm teaching five courses.

403
00:28:13,792 --> 00:28:15,487
I'm mentoring
two doctoral candidates...

404
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:17,662
...and I'm the faculty lifeguard
at the pool.

405
00:28:19,998 --> 00:28:23,525
- I just thought you could possibly...
- Perhaps you should keep a journal.

406
00:28:23,735 --> 00:28:25,703
Write down what she said
or something.

407
00:28:25,904 --> 00:28:28,634
That's all I can suggest.

408
00:28:30,642 --> 00:28:33,236
I can barely remember it all.
I just remember:

409
00:28:33,445 --> 00:28:37,939
"Little did he know that this simple,
seemingly innocuous act...

410
00:28:38,149 --> 00:28:40,617
...would lead to his imminent death."

411
00:28:40,819 --> 00:28:43,686
- What?
- "Little did he know that this..."

412
00:28:43,888 --> 00:28:46,652
- Did you say, "little did he know"?
- Yes.

413
00:28:48,126 --> 00:28:50,993
I've written papers
on "little did he know."

414
00:28:51,563 --> 00:28:54,657
I used to teach a class
based on "little did he know."

415
00:28:56,067 --> 00:28:59,730
I mean, I once gave an entire seminar
on "little did he know."

416
00:28:59,938 --> 00:29:01,769
Son of a bitch, Harold.

417
00:29:02,807 --> 00:29:05,640
"Little did he know" means there's
something he doesn't know...

418
00:29:05,844 --> 00:29:09,177
...that means there's something
you don't know. Did you know that?

419
00:29:10,582 --> 00:29:13,016
- I want you to come back Friday.
- Okay.

420
00:29:13,218 --> 00:29:15,448
No, "imminent,"
you could be dead by Friday.

421
00:29:15,653 --> 00:29:19,680
Come back tomorrow at 9:45.

422
00:29:19,891 --> 00:29:22,189
Ten seconds ago
you said you wouldn't help me.

423
00:29:23,995 --> 00:29:26,623
It's been a very revealing 10 seconds,
Harold.

424
00:29:30,702 --> 00:29:33,068
<i>Harold was deep in thought.</i>

425
00:29:33,271 --> 00:29:37,731
<i>For a few, brief moments, from</i>
<i>Born Boulevard to Euclid Avenue...</i>

426
00:29:37,942 --> 00:29:40,410
<i>... all the calculations</i>
<i>and all the rules...</i>

427
00:29:40,612 --> 00:29:44,912
<i>... and all the precision of Harold's life</i>
<i>just faded away.</i>

428
00:29:46,151 --> 00:29:49,917
<i>How perfect then</i>
<i>that in this space...</i>

429
00:29:50,121 --> 00:29:53,022
<i>... Ana Pascal would appear.</i>

430
00:29:54,325 --> 00:29:55,485
Ms. Pascal.

431
00:29:57,796 --> 00:29:59,991
Ms. Pascal, it's Harold Crick
from the IRS.

432
00:30:00,198 --> 00:30:01,665
Excuse me.

433
00:30:04,903 --> 00:30:07,633
- Hi.
- Hi.

434
00:30:07,839 --> 00:30:10,603
- Would you like a seat?
- Nope.

435
00:30:10,809 --> 00:30:12,834
There's 11 open ones.

436
00:30:13,044 --> 00:30:14,773
I don't care.

437
00:30:18,650 --> 00:30:19,742
Sorry about that.

438
00:30:31,529 --> 00:30:32,962
How are you?

439
00:30:33,565 --> 00:30:35,795
I'm lousy. I'm being audited.

440
00:30:37,202 --> 00:30:38,396
Of course.

441
00:30:38,837 --> 00:30:40,634
By a real creep too.

442
00:30:46,811 --> 00:30:49,405
I think I owe you an apology.

443
00:30:50,381 --> 00:30:52,872
- Really?
- IRS agents...

444
00:30:53,084 --> 00:30:56,485
...we're given rigorous aptitude tests
before we can work.

445
00:30:57,222 --> 00:31:01,556
Unfortunately for you, we aren't tested
on tact or good manners...

446
00:31:01,893 --> 00:31:03,986
...so I apologize.

447
00:31:04,896 --> 00:31:07,990
I ogled you.

448
00:31:09,801 --> 00:31:11,166
Sorry.

449
00:31:15,440 --> 00:31:18,034
Okay, apology accepted.

450
00:31:19,077 --> 00:31:21,807
But only because you stammered.

451
00:31:28,586 --> 00:31:31,953
So you're a frequenter of the
metropolitan transit authority too?

452
00:31:32,924 --> 00:31:35,256
No. I'm just late.

453
00:31:36,261 --> 00:31:38,491
Big flag-burning to get to?

454
00:31:39,664 --> 00:31:41,188
Actually...

455
00:31:42,333 --> 00:31:46,793
...it's my weekly evil-conspiracy
and needlepoint group.

456
00:31:48,139 --> 00:31:49,766
You wanna come?

457
00:31:51,042 --> 00:31:54,443
I left my thimbles and socialist
reading material at home.

458
00:31:56,281 --> 00:31:57,680
So...

459
00:32:01,152 --> 00:32:04,280
<i>Harold nervously made small talk.</i>

460
00:32:05,390 --> 00:32:07,756
You have very straight teeth.

461
00:32:07,959 --> 00:32:09,620
<i>Very small talk.</i>

462
00:32:10,895 --> 00:32:13,864
Thanks. They're real.

463
00:32:14,065 --> 00:32:17,398
<i>Harold quickly calculated the odds</i>
<i>of making an ass of himself...</i>

464
00:32:17,602 --> 00:32:21,436
<i>... in ratio to the amount of time</i>
<i>he stayed to chat.</i>

465
00:32:22,907 --> 00:32:25,034
This is my stop. I should go.

466
00:32:27,178 --> 00:32:29,578
<i>- He was elated and surprised...</i>
- See you soon.

467
00:32:29,781 --> 00:32:33,774
<i>... by his somewhat flirtatious</i>
<i>encounter with Ms. Pascal.</i>

468
00:32:34,285 --> 00:32:37,254
<i>So elated that he exited</i>
<i>the Transit Authority bus...</i>

469
00:32:37,455 --> 00:32:41,858
<i>... a good 27 blocks too early</i>
<i>and would now have to walk.</i>

470
00:33:00,778 --> 00:33:03,212
<i>- "You ain't down yet."</i>
<i>- That's right.</i>

471
00:33:03,414 --> 00:33:07,942
<i>Tell us, what is</i> You Ain't Got
Nothin' On Me <i>about, Emmett Cole?</i>

472
00:33:08,152 --> 00:33:09,710
<i>What does this mean?</i>

473
00:33:09,921 --> 00:33:14,756
<i>Well, it's about being around</i>
<i>in the world, doing different things...</i>

474
00:33:14,959 --> 00:33:17,257
<i>...doing what you wanna do...</i>
- Come in.

475
00:33:20,398 --> 00:33:24,391
Mr. Crick. Come in, come in. Please.

476
00:33:26,571 --> 00:33:27,595
How are you?

477
00:33:28,306 --> 00:33:29,534
I'm fine, actually.

478
00:33:29,741 --> 00:33:31,572
You can turn that off.

479
00:33:32,110 --> 00:33:34,601
Looks like our narrator
hasn't killed you quite yet.

480
00:33:34,812 --> 00:33:38,077
- No, not yet.
- Good, great. Have a seat.

481
00:33:38,816 --> 00:33:40,807
- Count the stairs outside?
- No.

482
00:33:41,019 --> 00:33:43,988
Course not. I've devised a test...

483
00:33:44,188 --> 00:33:46,656
How exciting is that?
- Of 23 questions...

484
00:33:46,858 --> 00:33:50,419
...which I think might help uncover
more truths about this narrator.

485
00:33:50,628 --> 00:33:52,459
- Now, Howard...
- Harold.

486
00:33:52,663 --> 00:33:56,497
Harold. These may seem silly,
but your candor is paramount.

487
00:33:56,701 --> 00:33:58,191
Okay.

488
00:33:58,669 --> 00:34:00,068
So.

489
00:34:02,273 --> 00:34:06,175
We know it's a woman's voice,
the story involves your death...

490
00:34:07,845 --> 00:34:09,403
...it's modern, it's in English.

491
00:34:09,614 --> 00:34:12,412
I'm assuming the author
has a cursory knowledge of the city.

492
00:34:12,617 --> 00:34:15,552
- Sure.
- Okay, good.

493
00:34:18,256 --> 00:34:19,985
Question one:

494
00:34:20,191 --> 00:34:22,682
"Has anyone recently left
any gifts outside your home?"

495
00:34:22,894 --> 00:34:24,452
Anything? Gum? Money?

496
00:34:24,662 --> 00:34:26,789
- A large wooden horse?
- I'm sorry?

497
00:34:26,998 --> 00:34:28,989
- Just answer the question.
- No.

498
00:34:29,200 --> 00:34:31,828
"Do you find yourself inclined
to solve murder mysteries...

499
00:34:32,036 --> 00:34:35,437
...in large, luxurious homes
to which...?" Let me finish.

500
00:34:35,640 --> 00:34:38,131
"To which you may or may not
have been invited?"

501
00:34:38,342 --> 00:34:39,536
No. No, no, no.

502
00:34:39,744 --> 00:34:42,770
All right. On a scale of one to 10...

503
00:34:42,980 --> 00:34:46,507
...what would you consider the
likelihood you might be assassinated?

504
00:34:47,085 --> 00:34:48,052
Assassinated?

505
00:34:48,252 --> 00:34:51,517
One being very unlikely, 10 being
expecting it around every corner.

506
00:34:52,390 --> 00:34:55,120
- I have no idea...
- Okay. Let me rephrase.

507
00:34:55,960 --> 00:34:57,951
Are you the king of anything?

508
00:34:59,030 --> 00:35:00,054
- Like what?
- Anything.

509
00:35:00,264 --> 00:35:02,562
King of the lanes
at the local bowling alley.

510
00:35:02,767 --> 00:35:04,166
"King of the lanes"?

511
00:35:04,368 --> 00:35:08,236
- King of the lanes. King of the trolls.
- "King of the trolls"?

512
00:35:08,439 --> 00:35:12,739
Yes. A clandestine land
found underneath your floorboards.

513
00:35:12,944 --> 00:35:14,241
- Anything.
- No.

514
00:35:14,445 --> 00:35:16,504
No. That's ridiculous.

515
00:35:16,714 --> 00:35:19,808
Agreed. But let's start with ridiculous
and move backwards.

516
00:35:20,451 --> 00:35:23,386
Now, was any part of you at one time
part of something else?

517
00:35:23,588 --> 00:35:25,749
Like do I have someone else's arms?

518
00:35:25,957 --> 00:35:28,983
Well, is it possible at one time
that you were made of stone...

519
00:35:29,193 --> 00:35:31,093
...wood, lye, varied corpse parts...

520
00:35:31,295 --> 00:35:33,661
...or earth made holy
by rabbinical elders?

521
00:35:33,865 --> 00:35:37,562
No. Look... I'm sorry. What do these
questions have to do with anything?

522
00:35:37,768 --> 00:35:39,895
The only way to find out
what story you're in...

523
00:35:40,104 --> 00:35:42,095
...is to determine what stories
you're not in.

524
00:35:42,306 --> 00:35:45,571
Odd as it may seem, I've just ruled out
half of Greek literature...

525
00:35:45,776 --> 00:35:47,869
...seven fairy tales,
10 Chinese fables...

526
00:35:48,079 --> 00:35:51,014
...and determined conclusively
that you are not King Hamlet...

527
00:35:51,215 --> 00:35:53,206
...Scout Finch, Miss Marple...

528
00:35:53,417 --> 00:35:57,080
...Frankenstein's monster,
or a golem.

529
00:36:02,226 --> 00:36:04,251
Aren't you relieved to know
you're not a golem?

530
00:36:05,296 --> 00:36:08,629
Yes, I am relieved to know
that I am not a golem.

531
00:36:08,833 --> 00:36:09,800
Good.

532
00:36:14,739 --> 00:36:16,434
Do you have magical powers?

533
00:36:52,076 --> 00:36:54,271
May I ask what we're doing out here?

534
00:36:54,478 --> 00:36:58,005
- We're imagining car wrecks.
- I see.

535
00:36:59,350 --> 00:37:01,614
And we can't imagine
car wrecks inside?

536
00:37:01,819 --> 00:37:03,343
No.

537
00:37:04,188 --> 00:37:06,418
Did you know
that 41 percent of accidents...

538
00:37:06,624 --> 00:37:09,115
...occur in times
of inclement weather?

539
00:37:09,327 --> 00:37:11,591
So do 90 percent
of pneumonia cases.

540
00:37:11,796 --> 00:37:16,699
Really? Pneumonia.
That's an interesting way to die.

541
00:37:17,635 --> 00:37:20,263
But how would Harold
catch pneumonia?

542
00:37:20,471 --> 00:37:22,462
Have you written
anything new today?

543
00:37:22,673 --> 00:37:23,935
No.

544
00:37:24,141 --> 00:37:26,939
Did you read the poems I suggested,
or make a list of words...

545
00:37:27,144 --> 00:37:29,112
...buy new typing paper, anything?

546
00:37:29,313 --> 00:37:30,871
No, none of it.

547
00:37:32,250 --> 00:37:34,013
Sitting in the rain won't write books.

548
00:37:34,218 --> 00:37:38,484
Well, that illustrates exactly how much
you know about writing books.

549
00:37:45,630 --> 00:37:46,790
What's this?

550
00:37:47,398 --> 00:37:49,730
It's literature on the nicotine patch.

551
00:37:51,102 --> 00:37:54,299
I don't need a nicotine patch, Penny.
I smoke cigarettes.

552
00:37:55,339 --> 00:37:56,601
Well, it may help.

553
00:37:56,807 --> 00:37:59,935
May help? Help what?

554
00:38:00,411 --> 00:38:03,312
Help what, Penny?
Help write a novel?

555
00:38:03,514 --> 00:38:05,744
May help save your life.

556
00:38:06,083 --> 00:38:08,517
I'm not in the business of saving lives.

557
00:38:11,289 --> 00:38:13,314
In fact, just the opposite.

558
00:38:16,394 --> 00:38:18,487
- "What's your favorite word?"
- Integer.

559
00:38:18,696 --> 00:38:20,220
Good, good, good.

560
00:38:20,431 --> 00:38:22,558
"Do you aspire to anything?"

561
00:38:23,901 --> 00:38:26,461
- No.
- Conquer Russia?

562
00:38:26,671 --> 00:38:29,231
- Win a whistling contest?
- No.

563
00:38:29,440 --> 00:38:33,308
Harold, you must
have some ambition.

564
00:38:34,111 --> 00:38:37,706
- I don't think so.
- Some underlying dream. Think.

565
00:38:39,984 --> 00:38:41,474
Well...

566
00:38:42,620 --> 00:38:45,248
...I've always wanted my life
to be more musical.

567
00:38:46,023 --> 00:38:49,424
- Like <i>West Side Story?</i>
- No.

568
00:38:49,860 --> 00:38:51,725
- Like...
- What?

569
00:38:51,929 --> 00:38:55,365
Well, I've always wanted to learn
to play the guitar.

570
00:38:57,835 --> 00:38:59,462
Okay.

571
00:39:01,305 --> 00:39:03,273
The last thing
to determine conclusively...

572
00:39:03,474 --> 00:39:05,965
...is whether you're in a comedy
or a tragedy.

573
00:39:06,177 --> 00:39:07,508
To quote Italo Calvino:

574
00:39:07,712 --> 00:39:10,977
"The ultimate meaning
to which all stories refer has two faces:

575
00:39:11,182 --> 00:39:14,049
The continuity of life,
the inevitability of death."

576
00:39:15,019 --> 00:39:18,386
Tragedy, you die.
Comedy, you get hitched.

577
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:24,161
Most comic heroes
fall in love with people...

578
00:39:24,362 --> 00:39:26,159
...introduced after the story
has begun.

579
00:39:26,364 --> 00:39:28,992
Usually people
who hate the hero initially.

580
00:39:29,200 --> 00:39:33,000
Although I can't imagine anyone
hating you, Harold.

581
00:39:33,204 --> 00:39:37,004
Professor Hilbert, I'm an IRS agent.

582
00:39:37,375 --> 00:39:38,569
Everyone hates me.

583
00:39:40,010 --> 00:39:41,204
Right, right. Good.

584
00:39:41,412 --> 00:39:44,677
Have you met anyone recently
who might loathe the very core of you?

585
00:39:45,783 --> 00:39:49,116
I just started auditing a woman
who told me to get bent.

586
00:39:50,121 --> 00:39:51,782
Well, that sounds like a comedy.

587
00:39:53,491 --> 00:39:55,322
Try to develop that.

588
00:39:57,128 --> 00:39:58,152
Four of these?

589
00:39:58,362 --> 00:40:00,296
You know, I didn't get my honey,
honey.

590
00:40:00,498 --> 00:40:04,025
Lulu, can you refill the honey
for Larry? Quarters also?

591
00:40:04,235 --> 00:40:05,827
That's my good boy.

592
00:40:06,036 --> 00:40:07,970
I'm adding some acorns.

593
00:40:08,439 --> 00:40:09,838
Mr. Crick.

594
00:40:10,975 --> 00:40:14,411
You're here early.
Must have a lot of people to extort.

595
00:40:14,612 --> 00:40:16,477
No. No, just you.

596
00:40:17,848 --> 00:40:20,646
- Twig tea and banana bread.
- Yes, ma'am.

597
00:40:20,851 --> 00:40:24,309
Actually, it should only take the day to
make sure 22 percent is all you owe.

598
00:40:24,522 --> 00:40:28,253
Well, I won't be paying no matter
the percentage, Mr. Crick.

599
00:40:28,459 --> 00:40:32,327
No, I know. But the percent
determines how big your cell is.

600
00:40:39,003 --> 00:40:40,630
You know, you can call me Harold.

601
00:40:40,838 --> 00:40:44,001
Yeah, I know. But I don't want to.

602
00:40:46,210 --> 00:40:47,404
This is for Ramona, honey.

603
00:40:47,611 --> 00:40:50,307
- Oh, thank you.
- You're very welcome.

604
00:40:50,948 --> 00:40:52,916
What is that?
What are you marking?

605
00:40:54,785 --> 00:40:56,309
Oh, this is nothing.

606
00:40:56,520 --> 00:40:59,648
Why don't we start
with your backup documents...

607
00:40:59,857 --> 00:41:02,325
...and the receipts
for the past three years.

608
00:41:02,526 --> 00:41:04,016
Sure.

609
00:41:12,703 --> 00:41:13,897
What's this?

610
00:41:15,306 --> 00:41:17,399
- My files.
- What?

611
00:41:17,608 --> 00:41:19,098
My tax files.

612
00:41:20,010 --> 00:41:21,500
You keep your files like this?

613
00:41:21,712 --> 00:41:24,510
No, actually I'm quite fastidious.

614
00:41:24,715 --> 00:41:28,242
I put them in this box
just to screw with you.

615
00:41:41,799 --> 00:41:45,132
- Hi.
- Hi. How are you?

616
00:41:46,270 --> 00:41:48,932
So how was it? Aruba.

617
00:41:49,139 --> 00:41:52,438
Ms. Pascal? Can I just ask you
a question about this receipt?

618
00:41:52,643 --> 00:41:55,510
- It was fantastic.
- Just wondering if this nine is a seven.

619
00:41:55,713 --> 00:41:58,944
- And what did you do?
- I got a beautiful tan.

620
00:41:59,583 --> 00:42:03,110
- I'm just gonna guess it's a seven.
- I mean, I feel stress-free.

621
00:42:08,392 --> 00:42:10,087
Do you need help with that?

622
00:42:11,295 --> 00:42:13,320
- Walk to heaven. I see the president.

623
00:42:13,531 --> 00:42:15,692
- It's the taxman. Hello, Mr. Taxman.
- Yeah.

624
00:42:15,900 --> 00:42:17,367
- You can call me Harold.
- Okay.

625
00:42:17,568 --> 00:42:19,195
- How the numbers going?
- Pretty good.

626
00:42:19,403 --> 00:42:21,166
- Gonna find that 22 percent?
- 22 percent?

627
00:42:21,372 --> 00:42:23,863
Twenty-two, 11 times 2.
It's prime numbers.

628
00:42:24,074 --> 00:42:27,066
- You gonna tax the bathroom?
- No, I'm not gonna tax the bathroom.

629
00:42:27,278 --> 00:42:29,542
- Could I use the bathroom, then?
- Go for it.

630
00:42:29,747 --> 00:42:31,442
Okay. I wanna use the bathroom.
Bye now.

631
00:42:31,649 --> 00:42:32,775
Bye-bye.

632
00:43:14,725 --> 00:43:16,090
Well, good night.

633
00:43:17,227 --> 00:43:18,888
You want a cookie?

634
00:43:19,530 --> 00:43:20,656
Oh, no.

635
00:43:20,864 --> 00:43:24,960
Come on. They're warm and gooey.
They're fresh out of the oven.

636
00:43:25,703 --> 00:43:27,500
No, I don't like cookies.

637
00:43:29,540 --> 00:43:31,167
You don't like cookies?

638
00:43:34,278 --> 00:43:37,372
- What's wrong with you?
- I don't know.

639
00:43:37,581 --> 00:43:40,516
- Everybody likes cookies.
- No, I know.

640
00:43:40,718 --> 00:43:44,620
I mean, after a really awful,
no-good day...

641
00:43:44,822 --> 00:43:47,723
...didn't your mama ever make you
milk and cookies?

642
00:43:48,892 --> 00:43:52,384
No. My mother didn't bake.

643
00:43:52,596 --> 00:43:55,724
The only cookies I ever had
were store-bought.

644
00:43:58,268 --> 00:44:01,101
Okay. Sit down.

645
00:44:01,739 --> 00:44:03,866
- No, I'm...
- No.

646
00:44:04,341 --> 00:44:06,138
Sit down.

647
00:44:10,014 --> 00:44:11,208
Now...

648
00:44:12,216 --> 00:44:14,241
...eat a cookie.

649
00:44:14,451 --> 00:44:15,816
I really can't.

650
00:44:16,020 --> 00:44:19,353
Mr. Crick, it was a really awful day.

651
00:44:20,257 --> 00:44:23,090
I know, I made sure of it.

652
00:44:23,594 --> 00:44:25,289
So pick up the cookie...

653
00:44:25,496 --> 00:44:27,623
...dip it in the milk...

654
00:44:27,831 --> 00:44:29,628
...and eat it.

655
00:44:54,191 --> 00:44:56,523
That's a really, really good cookie.

656
00:45:04,835 --> 00:45:06,632
So when did you decide
to become a baker?

657
00:45:07,905 --> 00:45:10,806
- In college.
- Oh, like a cooking college?

658
00:45:11,942 --> 00:45:15,070
I went to Harvard Law actually.

659
00:45:15,646 --> 00:45:20,777
- Oh, I'm sorry, I just assumed it was...
- No. No, it's fine. I didn't finish.

660
00:45:21,552 --> 00:45:23,520
- Did something happen?
- No.

661
00:45:24,922 --> 00:45:28,915
I was barely accepted.
I mean, really barely.

662
00:45:29,126 --> 00:45:32,254
The only reason they let me come
was because of my essay.

663
00:45:32,463 --> 00:45:36,456
How I was gonna make the world
a better place with my degree.

664
00:45:37,234 --> 00:45:41,967
Anyway, we would have to participate
in these study sessions...

665
00:45:42,172 --> 00:45:45,164
...my classmates and I,
sometimes all night long.

666
00:45:45,375 --> 00:45:49,106
And so I'd bake so no one
would go hungry while we worked.

667
00:45:49,313 --> 00:45:52,282
Sometimes I would bake all afternoon
in the kitchen in the dorm...

668
00:45:52,483 --> 00:45:56,510
...and then I'd bring my little treats
to the study groups...

669
00:45:56,720 --> 00:45:58,347
...and people loved them.

670
00:45:58,555 --> 00:45:59,817
Eat.

671
00:46:00,023 --> 00:46:04,289
I made oatmeal cookies,
peanut-butter bars...

672
00:46:04,762 --> 00:46:08,198
...dark-chocolate
macadamia-nut wedges.

673
00:46:08,398 --> 00:46:10,730
And everyone would eat
and stay happy...

674
00:46:10,934 --> 00:46:13,095
...and study harder
and do better on the tests.

675
00:46:13,303 --> 00:46:15,999
More and more people started
coming to the study groups...

676
00:46:16,206 --> 00:46:18,037
...and I'd bring more snacks.

677
00:46:18,242 --> 00:46:20,767
I was always looking
for better and better recipes...

678
00:46:20,978 --> 00:46:26,507
...until soon it was ricotta cheese
and apricot croissants...

679
00:46:27,384 --> 00:46:29,909
...and mocha bars
with an almond glaze...

680
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:34,750
...and lemon chiffon cake
with zesty peach icing.

681
00:46:35,859 --> 00:46:39,886
And at the end of the semester
I had 27 study partners...

682
00:46:40,097 --> 00:46:43,533
...eight Mead journals
filled with recipes...

683
00:46:43,734 --> 00:46:45,258
...and a D average.

684
00:46:46,203 --> 00:46:48,000
So I dropped out.

685
00:46:48,605 --> 00:46:51,130
I figured if I was gonna
make the world a better place...

686
00:46:51,341 --> 00:46:53,502
...I would do it with cookies.

687
00:46:58,348 --> 00:46:59,781
You like them?

688
00:47:01,285 --> 00:47:02,274
I do.

689
00:47:03,353 --> 00:47:05,150
I'm glad.

690
00:47:06,223 --> 00:47:08,282
Thank you for forcing me
to eat them.

691
00:47:09,059 --> 00:47:10,822
You're welcome.

692
00:47:16,099 --> 00:47:18,863
I should go. Oh, thank you.
For the cookies, I mean.

693
00:47:19,069 --> 00:47:20,832
- Why don't you take them home?
- Oh, no.

694
00:47:21,038 --> 00:47:23,199
- Oh, come on.
- No, really, please.

695
00:47:23,407 --> 00:47:26,433
- No, really, please.
- No, no, no. Really, please.

696
00:47:26,643 --> 00:47:28,702
I would like to, but I can't.

697
00:47:29,379 --> 00:47:30,903
- You can't?
- No, no, I mean...

698
00:47:31,114 --> 00:47:33,810
Because, see, it constitutes a gift.

699
00:47:34,151 --> 00:47:36,711
Actually I shouldn't have even had
those other ones, so...

700
00:47:36,920 --> 00:47:39,115
Okay. Well, I'm not
gonna tell anyone.

701
00:47:39,323 --> 00:47:41,951
- No. I know, but if you did...
- Well, I'm not going to.

702
00:47:42,159 --> 00:47:43,251
I know, but if you did...

703
00:47:43,460 --> 00:47:46,520
- What, you think I'm gonna call the...?
- No, no. I'll purchase them.

704
00:47:46,730 --> 00:47:49,858
I'm happy to purchase them.
How's that?

705
00:47:51,902 --> 00:47:54,302
And then there are no issues.

706
00:47:56,406 --> 00:47:58,636
- What?
- No.

707
00:47:58,842 --> 00:48:00,901
- Please.
- Just...

708
00:48:01,111 --> 00:48:02,942
- Why don't I just...?
- Go home.

