Anyway...

1024
01:11:05,861 --> 01:11:10,389
...let me quickly copy this list for you,
just in case.

1025
01:11:12,101 --> 01:11:14,501
Sociopathic author.

1026
01:11:14,703 --> 01:11:17,365
- I just wanted to thank you.
- Of course.

1027
01:11:17,840 --> 01:11:21,776
Listen, please, you must tell me if you
hear the voice of the narrator again...

1028
01:11:21,977 --> 01:11:23,444
...just for my own edification.

1029
01:11:23,646 --> 01:11:25,136
I will.

1030
01:11:27,783 --> 01:11:30,274
<i>Well, it's called</i> Death and Taxes.

1031
01:11:30,486 --> 01:11:33,216
<i>Wow. You know, I'm from Texas.</i>

1032
01:11:33,422 --> 01:11:36,983
<i>No. Not "Texas." Taxes.</i>

1033
01:11:37,192 --> 01:11:39,387
Death and Taxes.
Death and Taxes.

1034
01:11:39,595 --> 01:11:41,529
<i>Taxes.</i>
<i>Like the Benjamin Franklin quote.</i>

1035
01:11:41,730 --> 01:11:43,595
<i>Precisely so.</i>

1036
01:11:43,799 --> 01:11:45,733
<i>This lady's a package,</i>
<i>I'm telling you.</i>

1037
01:11:45,934 --> 01:11:49,426
<i>Tell us, what is this next book</i>
<i>going to be about?</i>

1038
01:11:49,638 --> 01:11:52,106
<i>It's about interconnectivity.</i>

1039
01:11:53,409 --> 01:11:56,071
<i>The looming certainty of death.</i>

1040
01:11:56,278 --> 01:11:57,905
<i>Men's fashion accessories.</i>

1041
01:11:58,113 --> 01:12:00,013
- Oh, my God, that's her.
- What?

1042
01:12:00,215 --> 01:12:03,275
- That's the voice. She's the narrator.
- No, that can't be right.

1043
01:12:03,485 --> 01:12:05,146
No, I'm positive.

1044
01:12:05,354 --> 01:12:07,754
Harold, this interview's a decade old.

1045
01:12:07,956 --> 01:12:10,618
<i>I didn't think anyone actually</i>
<i>wore cuff links anymore.</i>

1046
01:12:10,826 --> 01:12:12,521
That's her.

1047
01:12:12,728 --> 01:12:15,458
- She's British?
- She's her.

1048
01:12:15,664 --> 01:12:18,394
- Karen Eiffel?
- Professor Hilbert, I know that voice.

1049
01:12:19,802 --> 01:12:20,769
Crap.

1050
01:12:21,570 --> 01:12:23,868
- What's wrong?
- First of all, she wasn't on my list.

1051
01:12:24,073 --> 01:12:28,737
I figured you would have mentioned
the accent and she doesn't...

1052
01:12:30,079 --> 01:12:31,046
She kills people.

1053
01:12:32,281 --> 01:12:34,715
- What?
- In every book she...

1054
01:12:34,917 --> 01:12:37,477
The books are all about...
They die. She kills them.

1055
01:12:37,686 --> 01:12:40,621
- Kills who?
- The heroes.

1056
01:12:40,823 --> 01:12:43,223
Four Black Veils. <i>What is that?</i>

1057
01:12:43,425 --> 01:12:46,053
<i>It's about a girl who loses</i>
<i>several members of her family...</i>

1058
01:12:46,261 --> 01:12:47,853
<i>... in quick succession.</i>

1059
01:12:48,063 --> 01:12:49,291
Where is she?

1060
01:12:49,498 --> 01:12:54,526
She's untraceable. Believe me,
I used to teach a class on her.

1061
01:12:54,737 --> 01:12:58,002
I've written her letters. I mean,
she's a hermit, she's a recluse.

1062
01:12:58,207 --> 01:13:01,472
Here. Here's the last book she wrote.

1063
01:13:01,677 --> 01:13:04,737
Look at the copyright. She hasn't
published anything in 10 years.

1064
01:13:04,947 --> 01:13:07,279
She had knowledge of the city.
Does she live here?

1065
01:13:07,483 --> 01:13:08,950
She used to, yes, but I mean...

1066
01:13:09,151 --> 01:13:12,120
Banneker Press. 2267 Wallace Street.
Is that her publisher?

1067
01:13:12,321 --> 01:13:15,484
You're not listening. I said even
if you find her she's not gonna...

1068
01:13:15,691 --> 01:13:17,090
Thank you for your help.

1069
01:13:17,292 --> 01:13:19,055
She only writes tragedies!

1070
01:13:19,261 --> 01:13:20,626
<i>I don't believe in God.</i>

1071
01:13:48,757 --> 01:13:51,658
Okay, he's bringing her flours.

1072
01:14:03,238 --> 01:14:05,832
Kay, where you been?

1073
01:14:06,842 --> 01:14:09,743
I went out to buy cigarettes...

1074
01:14:09,945 --> 01:14:12,709
...and I figured out
how to kill Harold Crick.

1075
01:14:13,982 --> 01:14:15,313
Buying cigarettes?

1076
01:14:15,517 --> 01:14:18,953
As I was...
When I came out of the store...

1077
01:14:19,254 --> 01:14:21,518
...it came to me.

1078
01:14:22,191 --> 01:14:23,488
How?

1079
01:14:23,692 --> 01:14:25,956
Well, Penny,
like anything worth writing...

1080
01:14:26,161 --> 01:14:29,221
...it came inexplicably
and without method.

1081
01:14:29,431 --> 01:14:32,662
I see. Then what happens?

1082
01:14:33,502 --> 01:14:37,700
It's perfect, actually. I can't believe
I didn't think of it earlier.

1083
01:14:37,906 --> 01:14:40,841
It's simple, ironic...

1084
01:14:41,343 --> 01:14:43,538
...possibly heartbreaking.

1085
01:14:44,847 --> 01:14:46,178
Is that it?

1086
01:14:46,515 --> 01:14:47,573
Yes.

1087
01:14:47,783 --> 01:14:50,547
- You wrote it on legal sheets?
- On the bus.

1088
01:14:52,221 --> 01:14:53,586
Well, then.

1089
01:14:56,959 --> 01:15:01,396
So I'll finish it today.

1090
01:15:03,465 --> 01:15:05,228
I'll let the publishers know.

1091
01:15:05,901 --> 01:15:07,926
I'll begin packing my things.

1092
01:15:08,136 --> 01:15:10,104
I appreciate it.

1093
01:15:26,288 --> 01:15:28,722
- Hi. Hello. Hi.
- May I help you?

1094
01:15:28,924 --> 01:15:30,949
I need to speak to Karen Eiffel.

1095
01:15:31,159 --> 01:15:32,524
- I'm sorry?
- Karen Eiffel.

1096
01:15:32,728 --> 01:15:34,923
She's one of your authors.
I need to talk to her.

1097
01:15:35,130 --> 01:15:37,064
Well, sir, she's not here.

1098
01:15:37,266 --> 01:15:40,360
No. No, I know. I need to find her.
I need to know where she is.

1099
01:15:40,569 --> 01:15:41,831
We're just the publishers.

1100
01:15:42,037 --> 01:15:45,837
Right. Of course. But there must be
a way that I can contact her.

1101
01:15:46,475 --> 01:15:48,636
We have the address
where her fan mail is sent.

1102
01:15:48,844 --> 01:15:51,108
No, I can't send mail. It's urgent.

1103
01:15:51,813 --> 01:15:53,075
How do you know her?

1104
01:15:54,182 --> 01:15:56,776
- I'm her brother.
- Her brother?

1105
01:15:57,319 --> 01:16:00,288
- Her brother-in-law.
- She has a sister?

1106
01:16:01,023 --> 01:16:03,355
No, I'm married to her brother.

1107
01:16:04,259 --> 01:16:06,887
Not in this state, the one over.

1108
01:16:08,864 --> 01:16:12,129
Sir, I'm gonna have to ask you
to leave.

1109
01:16:12,334 --> 01:16:14,632
No. Okay. Listen.

1110
01:16:16,471 --> 01:16:21,431
I'm one of her characters. I'm new.
I'm in her new book.

1111
01:16:21,643 --> 01:16:26,046
And she's going to kill me.
Not actually. But in the book.

1112
01:16:26,248 --> 01:16:29,843
But I think it'll actually kill me
so I just need to talk to her...

1113
01:16:30,052 --> 01:16:32,213
...and ask her to stop.

1114
01:16:45,834 --> 01:16:48,667
Hi, Harold. Nice sweater.

1115
01:16:51,840 --> 01:16:53,239
Hi, Harold. Phones are out.

1116
01:16:53,442 --> 01:16:55,137
Hey, Harold, 19 percent of 4632?

1117
01:16:59,448 --> 01:17:01,712
Hey, Harold. Back from your vaca?

1118
01:17:01,917 --> 01:17:04,317
Hey. Looking good.

1119
01:17:05,120 --> 01:17:07,520
- He looks terrible.
- Yeah, banged up.

1120
01:17:09,157 --> 01:17:11,022
Wherever he went,
I do not want to go.

1121
01:17:11,226 --> 01:17:12,591
Book me not there.

1122
01:17:15,831 --> 01:17:17,025
He's totally ignoring me.

1123
01:17:20,736 --> 01:17:22,499
Here, look at this now.
There he goes.

1124
01:17:22,704 --> 01:17:23,898
It was good having you.

1125
01:17:47,429 --> 01:17:50,227
- Oh, dude, the phones are out.
- Can I borrow your cell phone?

1126
01:17:50,432 --> 01:17:52,696
- The signal's down.
- Damn it.

1127
01:17:52,901 --> 01:17:55,392
- You all right?
- Dave, I need a favor.

1128
01:17:55,604 --> 01:17:58,266
- Sure, what is it?
- Can I have some change?

1129
01:18:01,610 --> 01:18:04,636
<i>Within moments, Harold found himself</i>
<i>running across the plaza...</i>

1130
01:18:04,846 --> 01:18:06,814
<i>... heading for the nearest</i>
<i>pay phone.</i>

1131
01:18:10,118 --> 01:18:11,779
<i>At last, he spotted it.</i>

1132
01:18:14,156 --> 01:18:17,091
<i>But as Harold neared the phone,</i>
<i>he saw it was occupied...</i>

1133
01:18:17,292 --> 01:18:20,591
<i>... by an octogenarian determined</i>
<i>to reach his daughter in Denver...</i>

1134
01:18:20,796 --> 01:18:22,855
<i>... no matter how many quarters</i>
<i>it took.</i>

1135
01:18:23,065 --> 01:18:25,363
<i>Fortunately, Harold remembered</i>
<i>a bank of phones...</i>

1136
01:18:25,567 --> 01:18:27,330
<i>... in the Sixth Street subway tunnel.</i>

1137
01:18:27,536 --> 01:18:30,994
