1155
01:20:35,330 --> 01:20:36,524
Let him in.

1156
01:20:49,244 --> 01:20:50,541
Hello.

1157
01:20:51,012 --> 01:20:52,138
Hello.

1158
01:20:53,348 --> 01:20:55,043
I'm Penny. I'm Kay's assistant.

1159
01:20:55,250 --> 01:20:58,151
Oh, I'm Harold. Her main character.

1160
01:21:16,504 --> 01:21:18,131
Oh, my God.

1161
01:21:21,910 --> 01:21:23,537
Oh, my God.

1162
01:21:24,913 --> 01:21:26,540
Oh, my God.

1163
01:21:31,753 --> 01:21:33,015
Miss Eiffel?

1164
01:21:33,488 --> 01:21:36,685
Your hair. Your eyes.

1165
01:21:37,926 --> 01:21:39,484
Your fingers.

1166
01:21:41,730 --> 01:21:43,698
Your shoes.

1167
01:21:46,768 --> 01:21:47,962
Hello.

1168
01:21:52,173 --> 01:21:54,164
I'm Harold Crick.

1169
01:21:54,910 --> 01:21:56,639
I know.

1170
01:21:58,613 --> 01:21:59,807
How did you find me?

1171
01:22:00,882 --> 01:22:04,283
We audited you
a little more than 10 years ago...

1172
01:22:04,486 --> 01:22:06,477
...and your number was in the file.

1173
01:22:06,688 --> 01:22:11,318
I'm sorry,
but this is incredibly strange.

1174
01:22:11,526 --> 01:22:13,187
You're telling me.

1175
01:22:13,895 --> 01:22:15,988
Didn't you think you were crazy?

1176
01:22:16,631 --> 01:22:18,121
Sort of.

1177
01:22:18,333 --> 01:22:21,894
But then you were right
about everything. Like, everything.

1178
01:22:22,103 --> 01:22:24,298
And then you said,
"Little did he know."

1179
01:22:24,506 --> 01:22:28,636
- "Little did he know"?
- Yeah. It's third-person omniscient.

1180
01:22:29,277 --> 01:22:30,471
Jesus.

1181
01:22:30,679 --> 01:22:34,080
Which meant it was, well, you know,
someone other than me.

1182
01:22:34,449 --> 01:22:37,009
At least that's what
Professor Hilbert said.

1183
01:22:37,218 --> 01:22:39,311
Professor Hilbert?

1184
01:22:39,654 --> 01:22:41,315
- Professor Jules Hilbert?
- Yeah.

1185
01:22:42,624 --> 01:22:44,592
Yeah, he loves your books.

1186
01:22:45,493 --> 01:22:48,428
I love his letters. I don't...

1187
01:22:48,630 --> 01:22:50,655
So you understand
why I had to find you...

1188
01:22:50,865 --> 01:22:54,096
...and ask you not to kill me.
- What?

1189
01:22:54,569 --> 01:22:57,436
I mean, obviously
you haven't written the end.

1190
01:22:58,473 --> 01:22:59,440
Harold...

1191
01:22:59,641 --> 01:23:03,873
I mean, now since we've met
and you can see that I exist...

1192
01:23:04,079 --> 01:23:06,047
...you're not gonna kill me, right?

1193
01:23:08,984 --> 01:23:10,611
Have you written it?

1194
01:23:11,152 --> 01:23:12,710
I can... No.

1195
01:23:12,921 --> 01:23:14,445
- Have you written it?
- An outline.

1196
01:23:15,023 --> 01:23:16,888
Okay. But it's just an outline, right?

1197
01:23:17,092 --> 01:23:18,684
- Yeah, sort of.
- "Sort of"?

1198
01:23:18,893 --> 01:23:20,417
- It's just not typed.
- "Not typed"?!

1199
01:23:20,628 --> 01:23:22,118
- Maybe that's okay.
- What does that mean?

1200
01:23:22,330 --> 01:23:25,731
- I'm sorry, I'm trying to write a book.
- What do you mean it's "okay"?

1201
01:23:25,934 --> 01:23:27,959
- What do you mean you're sorry?
- Kay.

1202
01:23:28,169 --> 01:23:29,932
Let him read it.

1203
01:23:32,774 --> 01:23:34,537
Let him read it.

1204
01:23:49,391 --> 01:23:51,825
- Did you find her?
- Yeah.

1205
01:23:52,293 --> 01:23:55,626
- And?
- I may already be dead...

1206
01:23:55,830 --> 01:23:57,627
...just not typed.

1207
01:23:58,666 --> 01:23:59,655
Is that it?

1208
01:24:01,703 --> 01:24:03,000
Did you read it?

1209
01:24:03,204 --> 01:24:05,502
I tried, but I couldn't.

1210
01:24:07,075 --> 01:24:09,009
You have to read it.

1211
01:24:09,544 --> 01:24:12,138
You have to tell me
what to do or what not to do.

1212
01:24:12,680 --> 01:24:15,114
If I can avoid it...

1213
01:24:16,518 --> 01:24:18,486
If I have a chance...

1214
01:24:18,920 --> 01:24:20,410
Please.

1215
01:24:27,262 --> 01:24:28,729
Okay.

1216
01:24:29,397 --> 01:24:30,591
Okay.

1217
01:25:09,471 --> 01:25:11,564
And here's your uniform.

1218
01:25:12,774 --> 01:25:15,538
It's a go. Banetta's outside,
she'll assign you your locker.

1219
01:25:17,745 --> 01:25:20,646
- And you roll.
- I'm ready.

1220
01:26:17,906 --> 01:26:19,669
Professor Hilbert?

1221
01:26:21,543 --> 01:26:23,807
- Hi, Harold.
- Hi.

1222
01:26:25,747 --> 01:26:27,078
You look tired.

1223
01:26:27,815 --> 01:26:30,113
No, no, just calm.

1224
01:26:33,555 --> 01:26:35,420
Harold, I'm sorry.

1225
01:26:39,127 --> 01:26:40,856
You have to die.

1226
01:26:41,863 --> 01:26:43,057
What?

1227
01:26:43,264 --> 01:26:45,755
It's her masterpiece.

1228
01:26:48,069 --> 01:26:53,268
It's possibly the most important novel
in her already stunning career...

1229
01:26:53,474 --> 01:26:57,137
...and it's absolutely no good
unless you die at the end.

1230
01:26:58,213 --> 01:27:00,010
I've been over it again and again...

1231
01:27:00,215 --> 01:27:03,844
...and I know how hard this is
for you to hear.

1232
01:27:07,922 --> 01:27:11,187
You're asking me
to knowingly face my death?

1233
01:27:12,293 --> 01:27:13,920
Yes.

1234
01:27:15,463 --> 01:27:17,090
Really?

1235
01:27:18,066 --> 01:27:19,363
Yes.

1236
01:27:29,077 --> 01:27:33,537
I thought you'd...
I thought you'd find something.

1237
01:27:34,682 --> 01:27:35,979
I'm sorry, Harold.

1238
01:27:38,786 --> 01:27:43,314
Can't we just try and just see
if she can change it?

1239
01:27:43,524 --> 01:27:45,992
- No.
- No?

1240
01:27:46,194 --> 01:27:47,593
Harold...

1241
01:27:48,463 --> 01:27:51,728
...in the grand scheme
it wouldn't matter.

1242
01:27:53,935 --> 01:27:56,733
- Yes, it would.
- No.

1243
01:27:58,840 --> 01:28:00,808
I could change.

1244
01:28:03,044 --> 01:28:05,171
I could quit my job.

1245
01:28:05,380 --> 01:28:08,008
I could go away with Ana.

1246
01:28:08,449 --> 01:28:11,043
I could be someone else.

1247
01:28:11,886 --> 01:28:13,979
Harold, listen to me.

1248
01:28:14,188 --> 01:28:16,588
I can't die right now.

1249
01:28:19,127 --> 01:28:21,652
It's just really bad timing.

1250
01:28:24,098 --> 01:28:27,158
No one wants to die, Harold,
but unfortunately we do.

1251
01:28:29,003 --> 01:28:30,527
Harold...

1252
01:28:31,205 --> 01:28:33,196
Harold, listen to me.

1253
01:28:35,310 --> 01:28:38,438
Harold, you will die someday,
sometime.

1254
01:28:38,646 --> 01:28:40,807
Heart failure at the bank.

1255
01:28:41,316 --> 01:28:43,511
Choke on a mint.

1256
01:28:44,452 --> 01:28:47,785
Some long, drawn-out disease
you contracted on vacation.

1257
01:28:47,989 --> 01:28:51,720
You will die. You will absolutely die.

1258
01:28:52,560 --> 01:28:56,018
Even if you avoid this death,
another will find you.

1259
01:28:56,230 --> 01:29:02,066
And I guarantee that it won't be nearly
as poetic or meaningful...

1260
01:29:02,470 --> 01:29:04,438
...as what she's written.

1261
01:29:07,775 --> 01:29:09,606
I'm sorry...

1262
01:29:10,812 --> 01:29:13,576
...but it's the nature of all tragedies,
Harold.

1263
01:29:14,515 --> 01:29:18,349
The hero dies,
but the story lives on forever.

1264
01:29:56,824 --> 01:30:01,090
- There's an empty seat right there.
- No, I wanna sit down over here.

1265
01:30:36,731 --> 01:30:38,096
Kay?

1266
01:30:49,677 --> 01:30:51,076
Kay?

1267
01:30:53,714 --> 01:30:56,547
How many people
do you think I've killed?

1268
01:30:58,619 --> 01:31:00,917
- Kay.
- How many?

1269
01:31:01,422 --> 01:31:02,719
- I don't know.
- Eight.

1270
01:31:03,558 --> 01:31:07,722
- Kay...
- I've killed eight people. I counted.

1271
01:31:08,362 --> 01:31:10,091
They're fictional. Get up.

1272
01:31:10,298 --> 01:31:12,266
Harold Crick isn't fictional.

1273
01:31:12,700 --> 01:31:15,464
- I don't...
- He isn't fictional, Penny.

1274
01:31:16,537 --> 01:31:20,598
Every book I've ever written ends
with someone dying. Every one.

1275
01:31:21,375 --> 01:31:23,775
Really nice people too.

1276
01:31:23,978 --> 01:31:27,937
The book about Helen
the schoolteacher.

1277
01:31:29,050 --> 01:31:34,215
I killed her
the day before summer vacation.

1278
01:31:34,989 --> 01:31:37,048
How cruel is that?

1279
01:31:37,525 --> 01:31:40,892
And the civil engineer, Edward.

1280
01:31:41,095 --> 01:31:42,528
The one I trapped...

1281
01:31:42,730 --> 01:31:48,259
...with a heart attack in rush hour.

1282
01:31:48,469 --> 01:31:50,300
I killed him.

1283
01:31:52,073 --> 01:31:54,098
I killed...

1284
01:31:55,176 --> 01:31:57,269
Penny, I killed them all.

1285
01:32:31,045 --> 01:32:33,445
Miss Eiffel? Miss Eiffel?

1286
01:32:34,749 --> 01:32:36,614
- Harold.
- Hi.

1287
01:32:36,884 --> 01:32:40,251
- I just finished it.
- You just...

1288
01:32:40,454 --> 01:32:43,252
Yeah, I read it all in one read
on the bus.

1289
01:32:44,158 --> 01:32:45,819
It's lovely.

1290
01:32:46,027 --> 01:32:48,154
I like the part about the guitars.

1291
01:32:49,230 --> 01:32:53,098
Well, thanks, thanks. Goo...
Well, listen, I'm...

1292
01:32:53,301 --> 01:32:57,863
No, I read it and I loved it.
And there's only one way it can end.

1293
01:32:58,673 --> 01:33:02,200
I mean, I don't have much background
in literary anything...

1294
01:33:02,410 --> 01:33:04,344
...but this seems simple enough.

1295
01:33:07,381 --> 01:33:10,782
I love your book.
And I think you should finish it.

1296
01:33:28,035 --> 01:33:29,935
<i>The night before his death...</i>

1297
01:33:30,137 --> 01:33:33,766
<i>... Harold unsuspectingly went about</i>
<i>some usual business.</i>

1298
01:33:35,276 --> 01:33:37,744
<i>He finished his outstanding audits.</i>

1299
01:33:39,680 --> 01:33:42,205
<i>He made a few phone calls</i>
<i>he had been putting off.</i>

1300
01:33:42,416 --> 01:33:46,216
Listen, does your program
have an age limit?

1301
01:33:46,887 --> 01:33:49,287
<i>And he traveled to Ms. Pascal's...</i>

1302
01:33:49,490 --> 01:33:52,721
<i>... where she made him meat loaf</i>
<i>and chocolate pudding...</i>

1303
01:33:52,927 --> 01:33:55,589
<i>... and the two watched old movies.</i>

1304
01:33:57,365 --> 01:33:58,992
<i>It was a nice enough evening.</i>

1305
01:33:59,200 --> 01:34:03,034
<i>And in any other circumstance</i>
<i>it would've seemed commonplace.</i>

1306
01:34:03,704 --> 01:34:07,105
<i>In fact, the only thing</i>
<i>that made this night significant...</i>

1307
01:34:07,308 --> 01:34:09,674
<i>... was the morning it preceded.</i>

1308
01:34:15,383 --> 01:34:17,681
I have to tell you something.

1309
01:34:17,885 --> 01:34:19,182
You do?

1310
01:34:20,087 --> 01:34:21,748
I do.

1311
01:34:22,556 --> 01:34:25,650
- Is it a secret?
- Sort of.

1312
01:34:25,860 --> 01:34:27,350
Tell me.

1313
01:34:29,063 --> 01:34:31,031
I adore you.

1314
01:34:34,235 --> 01:34:36,328
I adore you too.

1315
01:34:39,040 --> 01:34:42,476
- That it?
- No.

1316
01:34:43,678 --> 01:34:45,475
I have to tell you this.

1317
01:34:45,680 --> 01:34:48,274
I just want you to listen carefully.

1318
01:34:48,482 --> 01:34:50,040
Okay.

1319
01:34:51,385 --> 01:34:55,515
You can deduct the value
of all the food you give away...

1320
01:34:55,723 --> 01:34:58,248
...as a charitable contribution.
- Harold.

1321
01:34:58,459 --> 01:35:03,761
No, no, no. In fact it amounts to more
than what you're currently withholding.

1322
01:35:03,964 --> 01:35:06,125
And it doesn't break any tax laws.

1323
01:35:06,333 --> 01:35:10,531
Harold, the point
is to break the tax laws.

1324
01:35:10,738 --> 01:35:14,105
I wanna make the world
a better place too, Ana.

1325
01:35:15,076 --> 01:35:18,239
I think that means
keeping you out of jail.

1326
01:35:22,216 --> 01:35:23,706
Okay.

1327
01:35:24,385 --> 01:35:25,875
Okay?

1328
01:35:26,087 --> 01:35:27,554
- Yeah.
- Okay.

1329
01:35:27,755 --> 01:35:31,418
If you come over here...

1330
01:35:31,625 --> 01:35:35,823
...and talk a little more tax talk
in my ear.

1331
01:35:36,030 --> 01:35:38,362
Because I like it so much.

1332
01:37:01,315 --> 01:37:05,046
<i>Much had changed for Harold</i>
<i>over the past few weeks:</i>

1333
01:37:05,252 --> 01:37:07,220
<i>His attitude towards work.</i>

1334
01:37:07,421 --> 01:37:09,753
<i>His habitual counting.</i>

1335
01:37:10,057 --> 01:37:11,820
<i>His love life.</i>

1336
01:37:15,996 --> 01:37:19,363
<i>But of all the transmutations</i>
<i>Harold Crick had undergone...</i>

1337
01:37:19,567 --> 01:37:24,561
<i>... perhaps the most significant</i>
<i>was that today on his return to work...</i>

1338
01:37:24,772 --> 01:37:29,209
<i>... he was not late</i>
<i>for the 8: 17 Kronecker bus.</i>

1339
01:37:31,879 --> 01:37:33,574
<i>What Harold had not understood...</i>

1340
01:37:33,781 --> 01:37:36,181
<i>... about that Wednesday</i>
<i>four weeks prior...</i>

1341
01:37:36,383 --> 01:37:39,147
<i>... was that the time he received from</i>
<i>his fellow commuter...</i>

1342
01:37:39,353 --> 01:37:43,084
<i>... was, in fact, three full minutes</i>
<i>later than the actual time...</i>

1343
01:37:43,290 --> 01:37:45,588
<i>... and, therefore, three full minutes</i>
<i>later...</i>

1344
01:37:45,793 --> 01:37:50,492
<i>... than the time to which his watch</i>
<i>and life had been previously set.</i>

1345
01:37:51,565 --> 01:37:53,931
<i>Not the worst of errors.</i>

1346
01:37:55,302 --> 01:37:58,635
<i>But if Harold had not set his watch</i>
<i>to the incorrect time...</i>

1347
01:37:58,839 --> 01:38:02,400
<i>... Harold would have again</i>
<i>barely caught the 8: 17 Kronecker bus.</i>

1348
01:38:03,043 --> 01:38:05,170
<i>And he would not be approaching</i>
<i>the bus stop...</i>

1349
01:38:05,379 --> 01:38:08,576
<i>... precisely at 8: 14</i>
<i>this particular Friday.</i>

1350
01:38:08,782 --> 01:38:10,249
Excuse me.

1351
01:38:14,288 --> 01:38:15,915
Harold?

1352
01:38:17,358 --> 01:38:19,451
<i>An otherwise ignorable fact...</i>

1353
01:38:20,027 --> 01:38:21,688
<i>... until the unthinkable occurred.</i>

1354
01:38:55,462 --> 01:38:57,726
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

1355
01:38:57,932 --> 01:38:59,627
I need for everyone
to just stay seated.

1356
01:38:59,833 --> 01:39:01,357
Come on, son.

1357
01:39:06,507 --> 01:39:09,101
- What happened? I didn't see him.
- It was not your fault.

1358
01:39:09,310 --> 01:39:11,608
He was trying to help the boy.
Get your supervisor.

1359
01:39:11,812 --> 01:39:13,006
I don't believe this.

1360
01:39:13,213 --> 01:39:15,704
- It was all my fault, though.
- No, it wasn't.

1361
01:39:15,916 --> 01:39:17,110
Is he okay?

1362
01:39:17,318 --> 01:39:20,151
- It looks likes he's breathing.
- I don't think he's breathing.

1363
01:39:20,354 --> 01:39:21,651
Oh, my God.

1364
01:39:36,603 --> 01:39:37,763
Come in.

1365
01:39:41,475 --> 01:39:42,533
Excuse me.

1366
01:39:46,313 --> 01:39:48,543
Are you Professor Hilbert?

1367
01:39:50,250 --> 01:39:51,683
Yes.

1368
01:39:53,921 --> 01:39:56,412
Hi. I'm Karen Eiffel.

1369
01:39:57,224 --> 01:40:01,627
I believe we have
a mutual acquaintance.

1370
01:40:03,097 --> 01:40:05,292
Please, sit down.

1371
01:40:06,233 --> 01:40:08,758
No, I just came by to...

1372
01:40:09,837 --> 01:40:11,202
Here.

1373
01:40:14,575 --> 01:40:17,442
- Is that it?
- Yes.

1374
01:40:18,312 --> 01:40:20,007
Have you read it?

1375
01:40:21,648 --> 01:40:23,343
Is that all right?

1376
01:40:26,854 --> 01:40:28,378
Yes.

1377
01:40:30,924 --> 01:40:35,861
I think, perhaps, you may be
interested in the new ending.

1378
01:40:48,375 --> 01:40:50,240
Good afternoon.

1379
01:40:51,178 --> 01:40:52,907
Oh, hi.

1380
01:40:53,547 --> 01:40:55,845
It's a pretty brave thing you did.

1381
01:40:58,919 --> 01:41:01,945
Stepping in front of that bus
was pretty brave.

1382
01:41:03,557 --> 01:41:06,219
Kind of stupid, but pretty brave.

1383
01:41:06,427 --> 01:41:08,156
Oh, yeah.

1384
01:41:09,096 --> 01:41:10,723
Is that boy okay?

1385
01:41:10,931 --> 01:41:13,161
He's just fine. Scratched up is all.

1386
01:41:13,367 --> 01:41:14,994
Oh, good.

1387
01:41:17,471 --> 01:41:18,995
Am I okay?

1388
01:41:19,940 --> 01:41:21,805
Well, you're not dead.

1389
01:41:22,009 --> 01:41:24,807
On the other hand, it looks like
you cracked your head...

1390
01:41:25,012 --> 01:41:27,207
...you broke three bones
in your leg and foot...

1391
01:41:27,414 --> 01:41:30,110
...you suffered four broken ribs,
fractured your left arm...

1392
01:41:30,317 --> 01:41:34,219
...and severed an artery in your right,
which should've killed you in minutes.

1393
01:41:34,421 --> 01:41:35,615
But amazingly...

1394
01:41:35,823 --> 01:41:38,553
...a shard of metal from your watch
obstructed the artery...

1395
01:41:38,759 --> 01:41:41,694
...keeping the blood loss
low enough to keep you alive...

1396
01:41:41,895 --> 01:41:43,362
...which is pretty cool.

1397
01:41:44,698 --> 01:41:46,962
Yeah.
So with some physical therapy...

1398
01:41:47,167 --> 01:41:49,897
...a few months of rest,
you should be fine.

1399
01:41:50,237 --> 01:41:53,365
Well, sort of. We weren't able
to remove the shard of watch...

1400
01:41:53,574 --> 01:41:56,475
...from your arm without risking
severe arterial damage.

1401
01:41:56,677 --> 01:41:58,975
You'll be okay.
You'll just have a piece of watch...

1402
01:41:59,179 --> 01:42:01,443
...embedded in your arm
the rest of your life.

1403
01:42:02,082 --> 01:42:04,915
You're very lucky to be alive,
Mr. Crick.

1404
01:42:05,853 --> 01:42:06,820
Yeah.

1405
01:42:11,058 --> 01:42:14,425
- Dr. Mercator, Mr. Crick has a visitor.
- Sure.

1406
01:42:15,462 --> 01:42:18,989
- My God, Harold.
- Hey.

1407
01:42:21,702 --> 01:42:24,466
- I'm okay. It's all right.
- Harold.

1408
01:42:24,671 --> 01:42:26,161
I'm fine.

1409
01:42:26,373 --> 01:42:28,967
Harold, you're not fine.

1410
01:42:29,176 --> 01:42:32,577
Look at you. You're severely injured.

1411
01:42:32,779 --> 01:42:35,748
- No, I'm fine.
- What...? What happened?

1412
01:42:36,917 --> 01:42:38,544
I stepped in front of a bus.

1413
01:42:38,752 --> 01:42:41,550
What? Why?

1414
01:42:41,755 --> 01:42:45,384
There was a boy.
I had to push him out of the way.

1415
01:42:45,592 --> 01:42:47,651
What?

1416
01:42:48,562 --> 01:42:51,793
I had to keep this boy from getting hit.

1417
01:42:55,202 --> 01:42:58,296
You stepped in front of a bus
to save a little boy?

1418
01:42:59,206 --> 01:43:01,299
I didn't have a choice.

1419
01:43:01,508 --> 01:43:03,135
I had to.

1420
01:43:17,591 --> 01:43:20,685
It's... It's okay.

1421
01:43:21,995 --> 01:43:24,691
- It's not great.
- No.

1422
01:43:24,898 --> 01:43:27,332
It's okay. It's not bad.

1423
01:43:27,768 --> 01:43:31,101
It's not the most amazing piece
of English literature in several years...

1424
01:43:31,305 --> 01:43:33,637
...but it's okay.

1425
01:43:35,709 --> 01:43:36,676
You know...

1426
01:43:39,146 --> 01:43:41,444
...I think I'm fine with "okay."

1427
01:43:41,648 --> 01:43:44,173
It doesn't make sense
with the rest of the book though.

1428
01:43:44,384 --> 01:43:46,978
No, not yet. I'll rewrite the rest.

1429
01:43:47,187 --> 01:43:49,519
My assistant said
she'd go back to the publisher...

1430
01:43:49,723 --> 01:43:52,248
...and request more time.
- Why?

1431
01:43:52,693 --> 01:43:54,354
Don't know. It's awfully sweet though.

1432
01:43:54,561 --> 01:43:57,029
No, why did you change the book?

1433
01:43:59,466 --> 01:44:00,990
Lots of reasons.

1434
01:44:01,201 --> 01:44:03,931
I realized I just couldn't do it.

1435
01:44:05,239 --> 01:44:07,207
Because he's real?

1436
01:44:07,741 --> 01:44:10,505
Because it's a book about a man...

1437
01:44:10,711 --> 01:44:13,703
...who doesn't know he's about to die
and then dies.

1438
01:44:13,914 --> 01:44:17,611
But if the man does know
he's going to die and dies anyway...

1439
01:44:17,818 --> 01:44:20,286
...dies willingly,
knowing he could stop it, then...

1440
01:44:22,089 --> 01:44:26,082
I mean, isn't that the type of man
you want to keep alive?

1441
01:44:28,428 --> 01:44:31,261
<i>As Harold took a bite</i>
<i>of Bavarian sugar cookie...</i>

1442
01:44:31,465 --> 01:44:35,492
<i>... he finally felt as if everything</i>
<i>was going to be okay.</i>

1443
01:44:36,470 --> 01:44:40,031
<i>Sometimes, when we lose ourselves</i>
<i>in fear and despair...</i>

1444
01:44:40,240 --> 01:44:42,640
<i>... in routine and constancy...</i>

1445
01:44:43,744 --> 01:44:45,905
<i>... in hopelessness and tragedy...</i>

1446
01:44:46,513 --> 01:44:50,074
<i>... we can thank God</i>
<i>for Bavarian sugar cookies.</i>

1447
01:44:50,817 --> 01:44:53,547
<i>And fortunately,</i>
<i>when there aren't any cookies...</i>

1448
01:44:53,754 --> 01:44:58,487
<i>... we can still find reassurance</i>
<i>in a familiar hand on our skin...</i>

1449
01:44:59,826 --> 01:45:01,817
<i>... or a kind and loving gesture...</i>

1450
01:45:05,632 --> 01:45:07,099
<i>... or a subtle encouragement...</i>

1451
01:45:11,405 --> 01:45:13,737
<i>... or a loving embrace...</i>

1452
01:45:16,009 --> 01:45:18,842
<i>... or an offer of comfort.</i>

1453
01:45:19,613 --> 01:45:23,344
<i>Not to mention hospital gurneys...</i>

1454
01:45:25,319 --> 01:45:27,446
<i>... and nose plugs...</i>

1455
01:45:34,161 --> 01:45:36,527
<i>... and uneaten Danish...</i>

1456
01:45:38,632 --> 01:45:40,759
<i>... and soft-spoken secrets...</i>

1457
01:45:44,671 --> 01:45:47,504
<i>... and Fender Stratocasters...</i>

1458
01:45:48,175 --> 01:45:52,839
<i>... and maybe the occasional piece</i>
<i>of fiction.</i>

1459
01:45:53,947 --> 01:45:56,245
<i>And we must remember</i>
<i>that all these things...</i>

1460
01:45:56,450 --> 01:45:58,611
<i>... the nuances, the anomalies,</i>
<i>the subtleties...</i>

1461
01:45:58,819 --> 01:46:00,878
<i>... which we assume</i>
<i>only accessorize our days...</i>

1462
01:46:01,088 --> 01:46:05,422
<i>... are, in fact, here for a much larger</i>
<i>and nobler cause:</i>

1463
01:46:05,726 --> 01:46:08,923
<i>They are here to save our lives.</i>

1464
01:46:09,563 --> 01:46:12,157
<i>I know the idea seems strange.</i>

1465
01:46:12,366 --> 01:46:15,961
<i>But I also know that it</i>
<i>just so happens to be true.</i>

1466
01:46:16,970 --> 01:46:18,403
<i>And so it was:</i>

1467
01:46:18,605 --> 01:46:21,073
<i>A wristwatch saved Harold Crick.</i>

